{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17517552","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17517552"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:54:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:54:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12813"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12813","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12813"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.15,0.17,0.53,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5254"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54211"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5254","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5254"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12813"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39687"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1397"},{"type":"tags","id":"2040"},{"type":"tags","id":"3510"},{"type":"tags","id":"4534"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8926"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8963"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9564"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14782"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16380"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42816"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54211","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54211"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of worsening pain and numbness in her feet. She has a medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus, hypertension, and hyperlipidaemia. Her regular medications include metformin, amlodipine-valsartan and atorvastatin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 120/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. She has diminished vibratory and position sense in her feet bilaterally. Monofilament testing shows loss of protective sensation bilaterally. Her fingerprick blood glucose level is 13.0 mmol/L. Investigations reveal an HbA1c of 7.7% (\u0026lt;7).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step to prevent progression of this patient\u0027s neuropathy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Prescribe gabapentin","Refer to a podiatrist","Prescribe sitagliptin","Prescribe empagliflozin","Prescribe duloxetine"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms and signs consistent with diabetic peripheral neuropathy, including pain, numbness, and loss of protective sensation in her feet. Her HbA1c of 7.7% indicates suboptimal glycemic control, which is likely contributing to the progression of her neuropathy. The most appropriate next step to prevent further progression is to improve glycaemic control.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrescribing empagliflozin\u003C/strong\u003E, a sodium-glucose cotransporter-2 (SGLT2) inhibitor, is the most appropriate option. SGLT2 inhibitors have been shown to improve glycaemic control, reduce cardiovascular risk, and potentially slow the progression of diabetic neuropathy. By addressing the underlying cause - hyperglycaemia - empagliflozin can help prevent further nerve damage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrescribing gabapentin\u003C/strong\u003E is not the most appropriate first step. While gabapentin can be effective for managing neuropathic pain, it does not address the underlying cause of diabetic neuropathy or prevent its progression. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferring to a podiatrist\u003C/strong\u003E is an important part of comprehensive diabetic foot care, but this will not address the patient\u0027s suboptimal glycaemic control, which is the underlying cause of the patient\u0027s neuropathy and will result in progression if not addressed. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrescribing sitagliptin\u003C/strong\u003E, a dipeptidyl peptidase-4 (DPP4) inhibitor, could improve glycemic control. However, SGLT2 inhibitors like empagliflozin have shown superior benefits in terms of cardiovascular risk reduction and potential neuroprotective effects compared to DPP4 inhibitors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrescribing duloxetine\u003C/strong\u003E, a serotonin-norepinephrine reuptake inhibitor (SNRI), can be effective for managing neuropathic pain. However, like gabapentin, it does not address the underlying cause of diabetic neuropathy or prevent its progression. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, while a multifaceted approach including pain management and foot care is important in managing diabetic neuropathy, the most crucial step in preventing its progression is optimising glycemic control. Empagliflozin can help achieve this goal while offering additional cardiovascular benefits.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Diabetic peripheral neuropathy presents with symptoms such as pain, numbness, and loss of protective sensation in the feet.","Optimising glycemic control is the most important step in managing diabetic peripheral neuropathy, as it addresses the underlying cause and can prevent or delay progression.","A multifaceted approach to diabetic neuropathy management includes glycemic control, symptom management, and preventive foot care."],"references":["Pop-Busui R, Lu J, Brooks MM, Albert S, Althouse AD, Escobedo J, et al. Impact of glycemic control strategies on the progression of diabetic peripheral neuropathy in the bypass angioplasty revascularization investigation 2 diabetes (Bari 2D) cohort. Diabetes Care. 2013;36(10):3208\u201315. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3781573/","Sloan G, Dinesh S, Solomon T. Pathogenesis, diagnosis and clinical management of diabetic sensorimotor peripheral neuropathy. Nature Reviews.Endocrinology 2021;17(7):400-420. Available at: https://www.nature.com/articles/s41574-021-00496-z","Management of type 2 diabetes: A handbook for general practice. In: The Royal Australian College of General Practitioners [online]. East Melbourne, Vic. 2020. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/41fee8dc-7f97-4f87-9d90-b7af337af778/Management-of-type-2-diabetes-A-handbook-for-general-practice.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39687"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12813"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39687","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39687"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-01T15:40:11+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-01T15:40:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5254"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54211"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49: